WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.880
Hello, my name is Ryan Wade. I am a senior cloud solution architect for Microsoft specializing

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:18.360
in data and AI. I'm here to present to you a topic covering the R integration in Power

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:23.240
BI and why you, as R developers, should be interested.

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:29.240
I am very passionate about both R and Power BI, so much so that I wrote a book about it.

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:34.240
I understand that many R developers do not share the same passion about Power BI that

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:40.639
I do. Many of you all may be saying, why should I even be interested in the R integration

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:48.119
in Power BI? The reason why is because the Power BI community needs you.

00:00:48.119 --> 00:00:54.919
So before I get into the meat of this talk, I want you all to know what this talk is not

00:00:54.919 --> 00:01:02.000
about. This talk is not about me trying to convince you to replace your Shiny apps with

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.199
Power BI. You are able to do things in Shiny from our visual standpoint that you can't

00:01:08.199 --> 00:01:12.559
do in Power BI, and I'm not trying to convince you to make that switch.

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:18.199
I'm not trying to convince you to refactor the notebooks that you develop in Jupyter

00:01:18.199 --> 00:01:27.879
Notebooks, R Markdown, or Quattro, and replace that with Power BI. Those two different tools,

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:33.959
or those tools, have a different purpose than what Power BI has. So I would not try to convince

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:38.919
you to make that change. And also, I'm not going to tell you to start

00:01:38.919 --> 00:01:47.000
doing your R development in Power BI and ditch RStudio. I am not trying to convince you to

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.440
do that. Microsoft is not trying to convince you to do that either. Microsoft gives you

00:01:52.440 --> 00:02:00.519
the option to do your development in RStudio when you're writing code that is purposed

00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:04.040
for Power BI. So that is what the talk is not about.

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:12.199
What the talk is about is to address the disconnect between some R developers and Power BI developers.

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:18.839
Both sides have their own perception of what the other tool is, and often that perception

00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:25.080
is not correct. So we're going to address that. I'm also going to try to introduce Power

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:30.759
BI to some R developers that is not familiar with the tool. You've probably heard of it,

00:02:30.759 --> 00:02:34.520
but you've probably never really seen it in action, so I'm going to try to introduce it

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:39.199
to you and give you a high-level understanding of what Power BI is.

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:44.399
And then I'll give you some examples of integration so that you can say, wow, Ryan was able to

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:49.839
do these things in Power BI. Based off of how I see he's using the functionality, maybe

00:02:49.839 --> 00:02:54.639
I can do these other things that Ryan hasn't thought of.

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:00.559
And then lastly, I will show you how to get started. So first, let's address some of the

00:03:00.559 --> 00:03:08.720
disconnect. There are a lot of unknown unknowns that R developers have about Power BI, and

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:17.360
that Power BI developers have about R. From an R standpoint, when R developers look at

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:23.600
Power BI, they just see another GUI-based data visualization tool. Power BI is much

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:29.199
more than that. And in this talk, I will show you the reason behind that.

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:36.240
And then on the Power BI side, when Power BI developers look at R, they see a domain-specific

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:41.839
programming language that they think is just for data scientists and statisticians. They

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:47.360
don't realize that a lot of the things that Power BI attempts to do have been done in

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:52.080
R community for some time now, since the 90s. I think R was developed in the early 90s,

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:58.160
like 93. So the R community has been doing things from a data visualization standpoint

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:03.679
that Power BI, that the Power BI community had just recently started doing. So we will

00:04:03.679 --> 00:04:09.759
address that. On the other side, when I'm doing different types of talk, I try to tell

00:04:09.759 --> 00:04:14.479
the Power BI community some of the things that you can do using that tool that they're

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:24.480
not aware of. So now that I got that address to disconnect, let me introduce Power BI to

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:30.320
some of you that are new to it from a high level. Power BI is a data visualization tool.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:39.119
In order to do data visualization, you need data. And the data model that Power BI prefer

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:46.000
is a data model known as the star schema data model. The star schema data model is made

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.559
up of two types of tables, a dimension table and a fat table. The fat table you see here

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:57.839
in the center, and the fat table stores measures. You can think of a measure as something that

00:04:57.839 --> 00:05:05.119
measures and a business activity. In this particular simple example, we see that the

00:05:05.119 --> 00:05:13.279
measures are price and quantity. And then the fat table is connected to the dimension table.

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:21.440
And in the dimension tables, you have dimensions grouped by category. So you see in this particular

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:27.119
example, we have a store dimension, a employee dimension, and so on and so forth. You can read

00:05:27.119 --> 00:05:35.040
the screen. In those different categories, you have dimensions that you can group your

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.799
measures and your fat table by. Another thing I want to point out about Power BI from a

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:46.959
data standpoint is how the data is stored in Power BI. Power BI uses an engine called

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:53.440
a VertiPaq engine. And the takeaway I want you to get from that is that the VertiPaq

00:05:53.440 --> 00:06:00.399
engine, one, stores the data in memory using what is called column store indexing. And

00:06:00.399 --> 00:06:06.959
the takeaway you should get is that storing data in that fashion does two things. It makes

00:06:06.959 --> 00:06:15.119
performance, you know, some complex calculation relatively faster than what it will perform

00:06:15.119 --> 00:06:20.640
if you are using another tool. And in addition to that, the column store indexing increases

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:27.279
the memory footprint of your data by a lot. In some cases, up to a tenth of the size of

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:34.320
the original data set. So the second thing I want to point out is the built-in data wrangler

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:39.920
tool that's in Power BI. And this built-in data wrangler tool, if you are using Microsoft

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:46.000
for sale, this tool is built into that as well. This is like a gem that many people

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:53.760
don't know about. This tool is called Power Query. And this tool, using a GUI, allows you

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:03.279
to do many types of data wrangling tasks with low code. Super easy. A person who has no coding

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:08.880
experience can do a lot of complex data wrangling that we in our community will probably have to

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:15.760
write a dplyr script to do with no code. And in the instances where you need to use code,

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:20.640
it has a programming language underneath the hood called M that you can write some code to do

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:27.040
some things that you can't do throughout the GUI. Super powerful. And again, it's built into

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:31.679
Microsoft for sale, so it's a tool you should look into if you're doing any type of data wrangling

00:07:31.679 --> 00:07:36.559
in Microsoft for sale as well. And this is what the interface looks like. And you'll see that

00:07:36.559 --> 00:07:42.000
the interface is similar to some of the other Office products, so the learning curve

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:47.519
with getting up to speed with this particular tool is pretty shallow.

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:56.000
The feature that I like the best about Power BI are the calculated measures.

00:07:57.279 --> 00:08:02.959
What I like about calculated measures is the way they operate inside of Power BI. They are

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:09.359
what I call context-based, meaning that they calculate based off of the context that you put

00:08:09.359 --> 00:08:17.920
them in. So in this particular situation, we have a simple matrix where we're displaying three

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:24.559
different measures, and those measures are the cells amount calculated measures, and those are

00:08:24.559 --> 00:08:30.640
the cells amount calculated measure, the comparison cells amount calculated measure, and adjusted

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:37.440
comparison cells amount calculated measure. One thing I want to point out is that we look at

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:47.359
the highlighted cell. In that cell, the comparison cells amount calculated measure is calculated in

00:08:47.359 --> 00:08:55.679
the context of the AdventureWork brand and also the context of the comparison date

00:08:56.400 --> 00:09:03.119
filter that you see in the slide filter on the upper right portion of the screen.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:11.520
Notice I didn't mention the filter that was being applied by the other date slicer, and I only

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:17.200
mentioned the slicer on the right. That is because the programming language that Power BI uses, a

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:23.440
programming language called DATS, Data Analysis Expression Programming Language, it allows you

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:28.799
to incorporate some pretty sophisticated business logic inside of it, and in this particular

00:09:28.799 --> 00:09:37.119
situation, you can see that we were able to remove the filter from one of the slices,

00:09:37.119 --> 00:09:43.919
and we only kept the filter that was applied in the slices in the upper right. Super powerful

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:50.000
feature. You will be surprised at the type of business logic that you can encapsulate

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:53.119
inside of a DATS expression using Power BI.

00:09:55.119 --> 00:10:01.520
Then, of course, it's a data visualization tool. Just like any other data visualization tool,

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:07.919
whether you're talking about Power BI, Qlik, Tableau, I know we have a speaker talking about

00:10:07.919 --> 00:10:15.599
that particular tool. You can build dashboards and get as RC as you want. I'm not good at that

00:10:15.599 --> 00:10:21.200
aspect. I do everything pretty bland, but if you're a very colorful person, you can do that,

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:26.479
or you can pretty much do any type of visual you want in Power BI just like you can with any other

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:34.080
visualization tool. Now, up to this point, you may be saying, Ryan, you just described a pretty

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:41.039
awesome tool. Why do we even need the R integration inside of Power BI? How do we even benefit from

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:47.520
this? Well, this is my opinion, this little graph right here. This is my opinionated view

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:54.080
about how I think Power BI is. This is my assessment of Power BI using these four different

00:10:54.080 --> 00:11:02.159
categories. In these four different categories, you see in most of the categories, I think Power

00:11:02.159 --> 00:11:07.520
BI is a very awesome tool other than the data science modeling piece. It does a good job of

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:14.080
data visualization, data wrangling for most situations. Then from a context-based calculation

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:19.200
that I showed you earlier, that feature right there in Power BI is awesome. Now, the data science

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:26.479
modeling side of things is very limited. You normally would need the premium capacity version

00:11:26.479 --> 00:11:32.479
of Power BI to be able to leverage Azure Machine Learning services. You can do some data modeling

00:11:32.479 --> 00:11:41.599
there and then connect to Power BI from there. Or you can use some pre-built data models in the

00:11:41.599 --> 00:11:48.400
form of Azure Cognitive Services. So, from that standpoint, still, it's kind of clunky. I don't

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:54.799
really recommend it. But when you add R to the situation, you'll see that from a data viz,

00:11:54.799 --> 00:12:03.119
there'll be 80 to 90% of the time, you'll have a visual that's already baked into Power BI

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:09.599
or that you can get from the Microsoft Store to import into Power BI. But there'll be those edge

00:12:09.599 --> 00:12:17.760
cases where if you are used to coding in ggplot, you can create that visual easily in ggplot,

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:22.239
but you can't do it in Microsoft. That is what that orange is representing. Then on the data

00:12:22.239 --> 00:12:29.039
wrangling side, there are situations where you may need a regular expression to do some type of

00:12:29.039 --> 00:12:36.479
stream manipulation. Or you may need to do something that is pretty clunky to do in Power BI,

00:12:36.479 --> 00:12:43.679
but you can easily do it in dplyr. And those situations is represented by the orange there.

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:49.760
And then on the data modeling side, if you're doing something in data science where you want

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:56.559
to bring in scored data into your Power BI data model, if you're using Power BI in a self-service

00:12:56.559 --> 00:13:04.880
fashion, you can take those R scripts that you have that will ingest in data scored,

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:09.760
and you can take that scored data and easily adjust into Power BI. And that's why I added

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:16.479
that little orange for the data science modeling piece. So now let's talk about some examples.

00:13:16.479 --> 00:13:23.840
The first example is a very simple data science machine learning example using a data set that

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:28.799
if you were learning any type of data science, you're probably familiar with this data set,

00:13:28.799 --> 00:13:35.919
the Boston housing data set. And it's a very simple illustration of how you can take a model

00:13:35.919 --> 00:13:42.960
that was saved in the RDS file on disk, consume that model, and then consume the data that you

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:50.799
need for the scoring. And just like you do in any other situation with R, you can use that

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:56.640
model and the new data that you want to score, score it, and then present that data to Power

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:06.080
BI as a data set. If you had a more complex workflow, you all that went to the tidy workshop

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:12.880
here. Or if you're familiar with tidy models, you can use tidy models if you have a more

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:22.080
sophisticated workflow that you need to do prior to scoring the data. Once you score that data,

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:31.039
the caveat is that that data set needs to be exposed as a data frame. If it's exposed as a

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:37.840
data frame, then you can bring it into Power BI. If you have it in any other data structure list,

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:44.479
Power BI would not be able to read it. Another aspect that I like when using R,

00:14:44.479 --> 00:14:49.919
the R integration in Power BI, is if I need to read data from a data API. In this particular

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:58.400
example, I'm reading data from the U.S. Census. And I can easily consume data from a data API

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:03.679
using R. From a Power Query standpoint, they have some integration, but it's very concrete,

00:15:03.679 --> 00:15:10.799
and it's not as performant as using R. So, in this situation, I'm looking at, I'm integrating

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:18.000
the Census API, bringing in data, and exposing that data to Power BI. And you'll see that it

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.760
will be exposed to Power BI as a data set. That can be extremely valuable when you're using outside

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:30.559
data to bring more value to the data that you have in-house. Now, the thing I like the best

00:15:31.119 --> 00:15:36.159
is the data visualization piece in terms of the R integration. In this example, this

00:15:36.159 --> 00:15:44.719
visual is near to me. This is a visual where I was, it was the first visual I built when this,

00:15:44.719 --> 00:15:50.640
when the R integration became available in Power BI. And in this situation, you'll see that

00:15:51.359 --> 00:15:58.719
we are able to do things with R that we're spoiled, but the Power BI community don't even know

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:05.039
of some of these capabilities. One of those capabilities is the ability to have annotations

00:16:05.039 --> 00:16:10.559
inside of your graph. Now, in this particular graph, if you were to add up all the different

00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:17.359
classes, you'll see that those, the numbers don't add to the total number of countries,

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:23.840
the 235 countries. And I'm able to add information in my title about why that's the case.

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:30.559
For each individual violin plot that's overlaid with a boss plot, I'm able to give information

00:16:30.559 --> 00:16:36.640
about that, the number of countries that was in that particular class, and the trade balance for

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:42.320
that particular class. Those type of annotations in the Power BI community, they're not aware of.

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:48.960
And that's, those are one of the things that make it super powerful. Another thing is, if you want

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:54.400
to choose another year, you'll see that I can easily pick a button, and then that filter will

00:16:54.400 --> 00:17:01.280
be propagated to my R visual. And if I wanted to look at this and I say, okay, looking over to the

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:08.079
left-hand side, and I see that the Caribbeans, for instance, we have a positive trade experience with

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:15.199
the Caribbeans. If you look at the left-hand side, I can drill down further into that information

00:17:15.199 --> 00:17:24.160
and get detailed information using the Power BI functionality. So, this R visual, and we're on

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:29.199
the R side, we're used to be able to be this expressive with our visuals, but not on the Power

00:17:29.199 --> 00:17:36.719
BI side. And you as R developers should reach out to some of your people in the Power BI community

00:17:36.719 --> 00:17:42.479
and, you know, teach them how the R integration can be super beneficial to them. I gave you some

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:48.000
examples here, but there are many more examples that once you start digging into it, you'll be

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:55.920
able to find out more examples and your unique use cases you can use also to be creative with

00:17:55.920 --> 00:18:05.119
using that R integration inside of Power BI. That's the end of this presentation. If you want,

00:18:05.119 --> 00:18:11.439
you can go to this GitHub site, and I have a little GitHub repo that gives you some high-level

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:19.040
information about leveraging the R integration inside of Power BI. I appreciate you all coming

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:26.560
to the talk and listening to me tell you about this R integration, and I hope you go out and

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:33.119
spread the love of the R community to other Power BI developers and show them why we love the great

00:18:33.119 --> 00:18:40.560
programming language of R. Thank you.

